## Migration: `Thread.Abort` â†’ Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Why this breaks

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ (`SYSLIB0006`). `Thread.ResetAbort()` is also gone. There is **no way to forcibly kill a managed thread** in modern .NET.

### Pattern identified: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code aborts a thread that exceeds a time limit. The modern replacement is `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter` with cooperative cancellation.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a cooperative timeout.
    /// The work delegate must check the token to respond to cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Tasks use the thread pool; no manual thread management |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.GetAwaiter().GetResult()` | CTS handles the timeout; blocking retrieves the result |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.CancelAfter(timeout)` (via constructor) | Cooperative cancellation replaces forced abort |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cancellation |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Removed | No equivalent needed â€” cancellation is cooperative |
| `Func<T> work` | `Func<CancellationToken, T> work` | Work **must** receive the token to cooperate |

### âš ď¸Ź Critical pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.** If `work` never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. Callers must update their work delegates:

```csharp
// BEFORE â€” fire-and-forget, abort kills it
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
        Process(item);       // Thread.Abort could kill mid-iteration
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// AFTER â€” work must check the token
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();  // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

**2. Pass the token through the full call chain.** If `work` calls other methods, forward the token:

```csharp
// Bad â€” token is ignored inside DoExpensiveIO
token => { DoExpensiveIO(); return true; }

// Good â€” token flows to async I/O
token => { DoExpensiveIO(token); return true; }
```

**3. Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.** It holds timer resources. The `using` statement above handles this.

**4. Uncooperative code (can't modify the work).** If you truly cannot modify the delegate to accept a token (e.g., third-party library), the **only** safe option is running it in a separate **process** and calling `Process.Kill()`:

```csharp
// Last resort â€” out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("worker.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

**5. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.** The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` guard ensures we only convert **our** timeout into `TimeoutException`, letting externally-triggered cancellations propagate normally.

### Async alternative (preferred if callers can be async)

```csharp
public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
    Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

    try
    {
        return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

`Task.WaitAsync(CancellationToken)` (.NET 6+) lets the caller stop waiting even if the inner task hasn't checked the token yet â€” though the work still runs until it cooperates.
